article.description:
Just when it seemed Chamique Holdsclaw had been shut down, she pulled off three consecutive brilliant plays to
send the Washington Mystics on their way to another playoff
victory.
article.headline: Liberty fail to contain Holdsclaw

images.name: Holdsclaw_Chamique 020822 vert top
images.caption: Chamique Holdsclaw said she went to the basket with confidence.

article.linkText: Holdsclaw's brilliance has Mystics up 1-0 on Liberty
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense, rebounding, a strong bench, no
second-half turnovers and a tiring opponent kept the Washington
Mystics in the game. Chamique Holdsclaw won it.

<photo1>

	   Just when it seemed Holdsclaw was having a quiet evening, she
took over with three consecutive brilliant plays in the final five
minutes Thursday night to send the Mystics on their way to a 79-74
victory over the New York Liberty in Game 1 of the WNBA Eastern
Conference finals.

	   A give-and-go assist to Annie Burgess, a baseline move for a
layup and a rifled backdoor pass to Stacey Dales-Schuman capped a
12-3 run that put the Mystics ahead for good.

	   "Our team was out there making shots, so I wasn't really
pressing on the offensive end,'' Holdsclaw said. "Then, as time
went down, I saw some opportunities to make some plays, and I just
took it to the basket with confidence.''

	   Holdsclaw, the league's leading scorer and rebounding during the
regular season, added a 17-foot jumper on the next possession and
finished with 20 points on 7-for-14 shooting, nine rebounds and six
assists.

	   But a few other stats were crucial. The Mystics, who forced five
consecutive turnovers with a full-court press in the first half and
12 for the game, didn't turn the ball over at all in the second
half. They also had 14 offensive rebounds and got 30 points from
their reserves.

	   Finally, the Mystics had four days of rest after sweeping
Charlotte in the first round, while the Liberty had just one day
off after their three-game series victory over Indiana.

	   "The 11 games in 21 days caught up to us in the second half,''
New York coach Richie Adubato said. "We just didn't have the
energy to go get the ball on the glass. The four days rest they had
showed up. I probably should have used my bench more. We'll have to
look at that for Saturday, so we can stay a little fresher.''

	   Top-seeded New York will host Game 2 on Saturday and Game 3, if
necessary, on Sunday. Adubato said he's not going to practice
Friday so his players can get their legs back.

	   "We've been in this position before,'' said Adubato, whose team
lost Game 1 on the road to Indiana before taking the series. "And
we've always gone back to Madison Square Garden and played well.
Once we get our energy and go back home, we'll be ready to play
Liberty basketball.''

	   Tari Phillips, who dominated in the paint until tiring in the
game's final 10 minutes, led the Liberty with 21 points. Crystal
Robinson had 20.

	   Holdsclaw had scored just one point in the second half and was
4-for-10 from the field for the game when she took over. Up to that
point, rookie Asjha Jones and Murriel Page had kept the game close
by scoring 19 of the Mystics' previous 27 points.

	   Page finished with 17 points on 6-for-8 shooting for the
third-seeded Mystics, who are enjoying their best playoff run ever.

	   "You do everything you can to get that first win, because it
shifts the pressure to the other team,'' said Washington coach
Marianne Stanley. "But we also know what New York is capable of.
Indiana was in the same position and they didn't get it done.''

	   Holdsclaw's three dynamic plays put the Mystics ahead 71-67 with
3:15 to play. The lead was six before Robinson hit a 3-pointer to
make it 75-72 with one minute remaining.

	   But Holdsclaw responded again, making a one-handed 10-footer on
the baseline with 35 seconds left and grabbing the rebound at the
other end when Robinson missed a 3-pointer. Holdsclaw was fouled
and made two free throws for her final points.

	   The game was a thrilling, fast-paced series of swings, augmented
by the deafening din of the loudest arena in the league. The first
run came when Becky Hammon came off the bench to hit a 3-pointer
and made two assists to Phillips in an 11-0 run that gave the
Liberty a 22-11 lead.

	   The Mystics then went to a press, creating turnover after
turnover in a 20-3 run.

	   Then it was the Liberty's turn. They stayed close before pulling
ahead with six points in the final nine seconds of the half.
Robinson made a 3-pointer with a 8.7 left, and Hammon made a steal
at the other end and hit a running 23-footer at the buzzer to make
it 37-35 at the break.

	   Liberty guard Teresa Witherspoon sprained her left ankle when
she fell while making a layup late in the first half. She limped on
the court for 30 seconds before a timeout was called, but she
returned to played the second half with the ankle taped.

	   She finished with nine assists and just one turnover.

	   "I hope we don't have anything balloon up by tomorrow, or we'll
be in trouble,'' Adubato said.
